# A [[graphical]] [[representation]] of a particular emotion of the writer, used especially in [[SMS]], [[email]], or other electronic communication
## A graphic made up of [[text]] [[character]]s to represent such emotion; a [[smiley]] or [[kaomoji]]
##* {{quote-book|year=2006|author=Joseph B. Walther|chapter=Nonverbal dynamics in computer-mediated communication|title=The SAGE Handbook of Nonverbal Communication|editor=Valerie Manusov and Miles Patterson|isbn=9781782689454|page=470|passage=In a 4 by 2 experimental procedure, :)  ;)  :(  or no '''emoticon''' were inserted alternately in simulated e-mail message mock-ups}}
##* {{quote-book|year=2007|author=M. Yanagisawa, M. Kobayashi, Y. Kato, S. Kato, and D. Scott|chapter=Research on the emotions interpreted from emoticons in Japanese cellular telephone email|title=Supporting Learning Flow through Integrative Technologies|editor=T. Hirashima, U. Hoppe, and S. Young|isbn=9781586037970|page=271|passage=The range of interpretations was surprising broad, for instance the '''emoticon''' (-.-) had 16 possible interpretations}}
## An [[image]] or graphic icon used to represent such emotions; an [[emoji]]
##* {{quote-book|year=2007|author=Loren Abdulezer, Susan Abdulezer, and Howard Dammond|title=Skype for Dummies|isbn=9781118050798|page=61|passage=In addition to placing '''emoticons''' by clicking icons in the pop-up panel shown in Figure 4-2, you can enter the text representation in your text chat window. For example, to show the image of the '''emoticon''' with sunglasses, you enter (cool).}}

